FOOD POISONING - AUSTRALIA (VICTORIA) (02)
==========================================
[see:
Food poisoning - Australia (Victoria) 970321190834]
[1]
Date: Mon, 24 Mar 1997 21:58:17 +0800
From: Mathew Green <mg@multiline.com.au>
Subject: PORK ROLLS
Melbourne..Victoria, AU 22 March 1997
More than 100 people have become seriously ill after eating Vietnamese pork
rolls from a bakery on Saturday, according to the chief health officer of
Victoria.
Nine people including two seven year olds, and two people in their 70`s were
rushed to hospital with acute gastroentertis. Health officers had traced the
contamination to a Hotbread shop in outer Springvale. The shop was forced to
stop trading at 5pm yesterday. At this stage the organism responsible has
not been determined. More than 100 people have been treated at Monash
Medical Centre, the Dandenong Hospital and by local doctors. Most of the $2
pork rolls had been consumed by Saturday lunchtime, it
appears that the contamination is linked to the pork, which was brought in
and prepared on site.It was stated that some heat treatment was carried out
but was not
carefully or adequately done.
It was stated that no link has been established with the salmonella muenchen
outbreak that caused the deaths last month of a 79 year old man and an 86
year old women and the infection of another 29 people after eating
salmonella-contaminated meat.
This report appeared in the West Australian Newspaper, PERTH Western
Australia on Monday 24 March 1997.
---
Denis Green
Research and Development Director
Tower San Systems
Perth
WA.
http://www.multiline.com.au/~mg/legion7.html
